# Cross-environment line-ending and encoding policy (TASK-AR-511)
#
# Goal: text files are stored normalized as LF in the repository so that files
# authored on different OS / panes / LLM workers do not generate phantom diffs
# or "LF will be replaced by CRLF" warnings. This removes the dependency on the
# per-user `core.autocrlf` setting.
#
# Semantics reminder: for a `text` file git stores the blob as LF; the `eol`
# attribute only controls what the WORKING TREE receives on checkout.

# Default: let git auto-detect text vs binary, and normalize all text to LF
# (both in the repo blob and in the working tree). This single rule covers
# .py / .md / .json / .jsonl / .yml / .toml / extensionless POSIX hooks, etc.
* text=auto eol=lf

# --- Windows scripts that REQUIRE CRLF in the working tree to execute ---
# Batch / command files are run by cmd.exe and must have CRLF line endings.
# (The repo blob is still stored as LF; checkout converts to CRLF on disk.)
*.cmd text eol=crlf
*.bat text eol=crlf
# PowerShell scripts are conventionally CRLF on Windows.
*.ps1 text eol=crlf

# --- Binary types: never normalize or diff as text ---
# None are tracked today, but these guard against future additions being
# corrupted by line-ending normalization.
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
*.jpeg  binary
*.gif   binary
*.ico   binary
*.pdf   binary
*.zip   binary
*.gz    binary
*.tar   binary
*.whl   binary
*.so    binary
*.dll   binary
*.exe   binary
*.woff  binary
*.woff2 binary
*.ttf   binary
*.eot   binary
